This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with interpreting convolutional neural networks (CNNs) which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the paper mentions learning explicit representations of object parts in high conv-layers, which is a common technique in computer vision. 

The paper also involves machine learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a method to learn decision trees to explain the logic of each prediction made by the CNN. 

The paper's focus on decision trees and explicit representations of object parts suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The paper's use of semantic explanations for each specific prediction made by the CNN suggests that it may also belong to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's use of potential decision modes in fully-connected layers suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
